      <h2>Trade-Specific Recommendations</h2>

      <h3>Electricians</h3>
      <p>You need a mix of hand tools (screwdrivers, pliers, cutters), a few power tools (drill/driver), and hundreds of small parts (wire nuts, connectors, cable ties). The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0051QIJA6?tag=sciencesolved-20">DEWALT Tool Tote DWST24070</a> is ideal for service calls — grab it and go. For larger install jobs, add a modular <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00CBY2EIO?tag=sciencesolved-20">DEWALT TSTAK DWST1780</a> for screw and connector storage.</p>

      <h3>Plumbers</h3>
      <p>Pipe wrenches, soldering equipment, and bulky fittings don't fit well in soft totes. A steel chest like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00PP4U5DI?tag=sciencesolved-20">Stanley 15GAL Chest</a> in the van, paired with a small tote for service calls, is a practical dual-system approach.</p>

      <h3>HVAC Service Techs</h3>
      <p>You carry a specific tool set to every call — and it rarely changes. A tote like the DEWALT DWST24070 gives you the right balance of capacity and portability. If you also carry recovery machines and refrigerant gauges, add a rolling <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B08TQLRZ6W?tag=sciencesolved-20">BLACK+DECKER stackable system</a> for those bulkier items.</p>

      <h3>General Contractors / Remodelers</h3>
      <p>Your daily needs vary wildly — one day you're demoing, the next you're installing trim, the next you're troubleshooting. A modular system is your best friend. Start with <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00CBY2EIO?tag=sciencesolved-20">DEWALT TSTAK</a> and add boxes as needed. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00MYX6BGI?tag=sciencesolved-20">Stanley FatMax 4-in-1 Mobile Work Station</a> complements this perfectly by giving you an instant workbench.</p>

      <h3>Truck-Based Trades</h3>
      <p>If you live out of a pickup, maximise bed space with a <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0G3NPDQCK?tag=sciencesolved-20">LULU CARGO CONTROL Underbody Truck Box</a> for daily-use hand tools, and keep larger chests or modular stacks secured in the bed with tie-downs.</p>

      <h2>Can You Use More Than One?</h2>
      <p>Yes — and many experienced contractors do. The most effective tool storage strategy is often a hybrid: a truck-mounted or stationary chest for bulk storage, a modular stack for job-site transport, and a small tote for quick service calls. You don't have to choose just one system. Choose the combination that matches how you actually work.</p>

      <h2>Final Recommendation</h2>
      <p>If you can only buy one system right now, here's our advice based on trade:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mobile trades (electrician, HVAC, plumbing service):</strong> Get a quality tote first. Add a modular box later.</li>
        <li><strong>Stationary trades (framing, concrete, roofing):</strong> A chest or truck box gives you the best value for bulk storage.</li>
        <li><strong>Variable trades (GC, renovation, handyman):</strong> Modular is the only correct answer. It scales with your needs.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Your tools are how you earn your living. The right storage system protects that investment and makes you faster on every job. Choose wisely.</p>

